column3: ReverieHacks is the biggest and most unique virtual hackathon for students to showcase their projects to the world and earn prizes along the way. Students can join in teams of 1-3 in one of several tracks to design projects from their dreams and compete for various awards.&lt
Our hackathon features six distinct tracks, each designed to showcase and develop a variety of skills among high school students. These tracks are:&lt

column5: : A track where teams collaborate to brainstorm, refine, and develop innovative ideas into comprehensive project plans. Participants will have the opportunity to explore creative solutions, receive feedback, and turn their concepts into viable projects.&lt

: A track where teams design and optimize AI workflows to achieve the best possible results for specific purposes. Participants will focus on creating efficient and effective workflows using LLM models like ChatGPT and Gemini, employing structured queries to ensure the most optimized output based on the given input.&lt
: A track centered around traditional hackathon experiences where teams design software solutions to unique problem.&lt

: A track where teams use machine learning and data science techniques to analyze datasets and identify patterns to solve specific problems. Participants will not only be finding trends, but also analyzing them to gain insights into a possible solution.&lt

: A track meant for those interested in computer and electrical systems. Within this track, teams will be making use of ecad software for developing hardware solutions like pcbs for specific purposes.&lt

: A track meant for those enthusiastic about creating applications for mobile devices. Unlike software development where teams may present projects about any program, this track is specially for mobile applications.&lt

column3: Each track offers a unique challenge, allowing participants to highlight and enhance their specific talents.&lt
For more information you can check out our &lt

column1: Originality and creativity in the solution, including unique features or approaches. Out of 9 points.
How well the software addresses challenge and its impact on the target audience. Out of 9 points
There is a secret criteria for each track that represents it best and will be revealed at the end of the hackathon which gives bonus 3 points
,Student powered hackathon for students to make their dream projects come true through generative Ai.,

column7: For the ideathon track, you are required to submit 2 different files:&lt
Record a small video (no longer than 5 mins) which is your pitch that covers the purpose of your project as well as key details.&lt

A pdf document that covers all details regarding the project like purpose, technical details, mockups, logistics as well as your future plans for the project. It would be a good idea to include extra details in this document and focus only on key details in the pitch presentation.&lt

For the ML prompt engineering track, students interested in the application of LLMs will be designing workflows that help obtain an output for specific purposes through human input and structured queries via ML models like GPT, Gemini.&lt
For the ML prompt engineering track, you are required to submit 4 different files:&lt
Upload a png of the flowchart version of your ML workflow that depicts where human inputs is necessary, what queries are used with LLMs, which LLM model is used and what each action does.&lt
Prepare a video/document that shows the use of workflow for sample test cases as compared to using a single prompt approach with the same test cases.&lt
Include a detailed documentation that explains the reasoning behind each node in the Ai workflow, how it works and any other necessary data.&lt

The building process for the software development track is fairly simple and your goal is to create a software solution. It is important that you do it on github along with relevant licensing to help protect your project. It is also vital that you follow our guidelines which can be found &lt
For the software development track, you are required to submit 4 different files:&lt
Upload the complete project code to a version control platform such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket. Ensure the repository is accessible and includes necessary instructions.&lt
Create a video that demonstrates the functionality, features, and user interface of the software. The video should highlight key aspects and use cases.&lt

Provide a detailed Project documentation that includes information like purpose, target audience and main features, but also technical things like installation guides, user manuals, references and any configuration or setup instructions.&lt

The building process for the datathon track starts with identifying the problem you want to solve and finding relevant datasets. Datasets can be easily found on kaggle.com. The next step would be writing the code for exploring and processing the dataset, and then training a model around it. Finally, the team will work to interpret the results and derive meaningful conclusions from it, and prepare necessary documentation.&lt
For the datathon track, you are required to submit 4 different files:&lt
Upload the complete project code to a version control platform such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket. Ensure the repository is accessible and includes necessary instructions.&lt
Within your github read me file, you also have to include a link to the dataset used by you.&lt
Prepare a document that explains your results and analysis, the methodlogy employed, reasoning behind certain crucial decisions and your evaluation of the model training process.&lt
Create a video that best demonstrates your trained model or your results.&lt

The building process for embedded systems starts with finding a problem you want to solve. You can find find problems that you go through daily or inconviences that you face on a regular basis. Then comes the designing process. Starting with picking out the components you need, you should start designing a circuit. Once you are happy with the circuit you have designed and have created a schematic that works, you can begin converting it into a PCB.  You should be constantly using Design rules check (DRC) to ensure that your design doesn
For the embedded systems track, you are required to submit 4 different files:&lt

Upload the complete project to an online storage solution such as GitHub or google drive. Ensure the directory is accessible and includes necessary instructions. This should contain schematics of your circuit as well as any other design.&lt
If your circuit uses any MCU, then you must upload the relevant code in your file directory. It is highly reccomended to include a flowchart of your algorithm to make the code easy to understand. &lt
Create a video that demonstrates the designed product. The video should highlight key aspects and use cases.&lt
Prepare a document that gives tech specs and explains your product in detail.&lt

In the app development track, you will be building programming an app around the problem. However, it is also vital to consider other important factors like Ui/Ux while designing your app. Find more &lt
For the app dev track, you are required to submit 3 different files:&lt
Upload the complete project code to a version control platform such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket. Ensure the repository is accessible and includes necessary instructions.&lt
Create a demo video of the app, showing off its features as well as other features like the Ui.&lt

Provide a detailed Project documentation that includes information like purpose, target audience and main features, but also technical things like installation guides, user manuals, references and any configuration or setup instructions for using the app.&lt

column3: Dive into the world of cutting-edge AI with the Google Chrome Built-in AI Challenge! This hackathon invites developers to explore new ground by creating web applications or Chrome Extensions that leverage Chrome’s built-in AI APIs and models, including Gemini Nano.&amp
The APIs can give you access to:&amp

column15: create dynamic user prompts (Prompt API, Prompt API in Chrome Extensions)&amp
distill complex information into clear insights (Summarization API)&lt
improve your content with alternative options (Rewrite API)&lt

column5: Please note: all of these tasks take place in the browser, using the models downloaded to your device without a need for server calls.&lt

column3: This is your opportunity to experiment with these advanced capabilities and create helpful experiences that meet everyday needs.&amp
column5: From enriching user interactions to automating intricate processes, this is your chance to explore the uncharted territory of built-in AI and help uncover its true potential.&amp

column3: Entrants must develop a web application or Chrome Extension that uses one or more APIs to interact with Chrome’s built-in AI models, such as Gemini Nano. The APIs include but are not limited to the Prompt API for Web and in Chrome Extensions, Summarization API, Write API, and Rewrite API. &lt
Provide a URL to your public, open source GitHub code repository for judging and testing. The repository must include an open source license.&lt

column3: Please find the Application Requirements and Submission Requirements outlined below (hereinafter, referred to collectively as the “Requirements”).   &lt

What to Create: Entrants must develop a web application or Chrome Extension that uses one or more APIs to interact with Chrome’s built-in AI models, such as Gemini Nano. The APIs include but are not limited to the Prompt API for Web and in Chrome Extensions, Summarization API, Write API, and Rewrite API. &lt

Functionality: The Application must be capable of being successfully installed and running consistently on the platform for which it is intended and must function as depicted in the demonstration video and/or expressed in the text description.&lt
Platforms: A submitted Application must run on the platform for which it is intended and which is specified in the Submission Requirements.&lt
New Applications: Applications must be newly created by the entrant during the duration of the Contest Period.&lt
Third Party Integrations: If an Application integrates any third-party SDK, APIs and/or data, entrants must be authorized to use them.&lt
Testing: The entrant must make the Application available free of charge and without any restriction, for testing, evaluation and use by the Sponsor and Judges until the judging period ends.&lt

If the Application includes software that runs on proprietary or third party hardware that is not widely available to the public, including software running on devices or wearable technology other than smartphones, tablets, or desktop computers, the Sponsor reserves the right, at its sole discretion, to require the entrant to provide physical access to the Application hardware upon request. &lt
The Application must, at a minimum, support English language use.&lt

column3: Include an Application built with the required developer tools and meets the above Application Requirements.&lt

Include a text description that should explain the features and functionality of your Application. Text description must also include which APIs were used, and the problem you are looking to solve.&lt
Include a demonstration video of your Application. The video portion of the submission:&lt
should be less than three (3) minutes&lt
should include footage that shows the Application functioning on the device for which it was built&lt
must be uploaded to and made publicly visible on YouTube or Vimeo, and a link to the video must be provided on the submission form on the Contest Site
cannot contain any content, element, or material that violates a third party’s publicity, privacy or intellectual property rights.&lt

Include a URL to a public open source GitHub repository. The repository must include an open source license and should include instructions and everything the judges require to test the Application.&lt

Access must be provided to an entrant’s working Application for judging and testing by providing a link to a website, functioning demo, or a published application. If Entrant’s website is private, Entrant must include login credentials in its testing instructions. The Application must be public. &lt
Written and video parts of Entries must be in English.&lt

(Optional) Share your feedback on the development process with these APIs. You must have submitted a project to complete a feedback submission form and be eligible for the Most Valuable Feedback Prize.&lt

To be considered for the Most Valuable Feedback prize, entrants must have submitted an eligible entry to the hackathon during the Feedback Period, which runs from October 1, 2024 (9:00 A.M. Pacific Time) through December 31, 2024.&lt

Draft Submissions: Prior to the end of the Contest Period, you may save draft versions of your submission on Devpost to your portfolio before submitting the submission materials to the Contest for evaluation. Once the Contest Period has ended, you may not make any changes or alterations to your submission, but you may continue to update the application in your Devpost portfolio.&lt

Modifications After the Contest Period. The Poster and Administrator may permit you to modify part of your submission after the Contest Period for the purpose of adding, removing or replacing material that potentially infringes a third party mark or right, discloses personally identifiable information, or is otherwise inappropriate. The modified submission must remain substantively the same as the original submission with the only modification being what the Poster and Administrator permits. &lt

At any time, and at its sole discretion, the Poster will have the ability to re-assign a submitted Submission from one Category to another or to disqualify a submission for not sufficiently fitting the Application or Submission Requirement.&lt

All Entries must be received by 11:45:00 P.M., Pacific Time (PT) on  December 3, 2024.  Entries are void if they are in whole or part illegible, incomplete, damaged, altered, counterfeit, obtained through fraud, or late. All Entries will be deemed made by the authorized account holder of the email address submitted at the time of entry, and the potential winner may be required to show proof of being the authorized account holder for that email address. column3: The Hackathon is open to individuals who are at least 18 years old and are developers, designers, or other individuals with an interest in AI and machine learning (“you” or “Entrant”). Employees of Sponsor, as well as their immediate family members and household members, are not eligible to participate.&lt
To participate in the Hackathon, you must:&lt
Create a project that uses any of the models available on SambaNova Cloud.&lt
Ensure that your project is original and does not infringe on the intellectual property rights of any third party.&lt

Submit your project through the designated submission portal on the SambaNova Community website (the “Hackathon Website”).  The term “Submission” means anything you submit to the Hackathon via the Hackathon Website, including, but not limited to, the project and any description thereof.&lt
With your Submission, provide a detailed description of your project, including its functionality, features, and any relevant technical specifications.&lt
Make your project available for judging and testing during the Hackathon Period.&lt
The following prizes will be awarded to the winners of the Hackathon:&lt
Most Liked Submission on the SambaNova Community: $500&lt
A chance to win $500 for reposting the announcement on X. The winner must have submitted an application and re-tweeted our announcement post to be eligible. The relevant post is &lt
A panel of judges (the “Judges”) from and/or designated by the Sponsor will evaluate all eligible submissions based on the following criteria:&lt
Agentic AI (1-5 points): The extent to which the project innovates with Agentic AI by interacting with users and processing requests.&lt
Reusability (1-5 points): The extent to which the project can be reused by the Developer community to build Agentic applications.&lt
User Interface (1-5 points): The extent to which the project has a visually appealing interface to make interacting with Agents enticing.&lt
X Factor: Additional points given for projects that demonstrate extraordinary use cases not covered in other criteria.&lt

WaffleHacks is a 48-hour student-organized hackathon working to bring technical solutions to your local communities and small businesses. We welcome all students, of high school level and beyond, and of all technical proficiency levels, to join us on June 21st - 23nd, 2023.&lt

column5: Due to the pandemic, a group of first-year college students was forced to experience a summer of opportunity online. Stuck in quarantine, it was hard to form connections, especially going into their freshman year of college. However, this did not stop them from them creating a warm and supportive community. To pay homage to their unbreakable bond, they worked together and created WaffleHacks. The purpose of WaffleHacks is to inspire high school and undergraduate students to look within their communities and build new opportunities that would benefit the world around them.&lt

column1: How technically impressive was the hack? Was the technical problem the team tackled difficult? Did it use a particularly clever technique or did it use many different components? Did the technology involved make you go &quot

Inspire innovation in the next generation of students. Does it do something entirely novel, or at least take a fresh approach to an old problem? This category will be based solely on the idea behind your project, regardless of functionality.

We look for hacks that have large social impact. Is the hack impactful? Does it fulfill a real need people have? This category will be based on the idea behind your project and its planned functionality (not necessarily fully working).

We look for new and original ideas, we want hackers to think outside the box, but we also value practicality. Is this project feasible and practical in the next 3-5 years? This category will be based on both the idea &amp

column5: HACK.COMS is a 24-hour hackathon hosted by the Computer Organization for Multicultural Students (COMS). &lt
column9: COMS is committed to building a supportive community that celebrates the talent of underrepresented students in computing.&lt
column13: A hackathon is a collaborative event where developers, designers, and tech enthusiasts come together to create a project within a limited time frame, typically ranging from a few hours to a few days. The focus is on creativity, innovation, and teamwork, and the end result is a functional project that is often shared and utilized in the community.&lt
column17: This year, alongside our traditional hackathon, we&#39

This category is a collaboration between HACK.COMS and the Multicultural Business Association @ RIT. &lt

column5: Outshine the ordinary at Eclipse Hacks by driving tech solutions for a sustainable future!&lt

column3: Eclipse Hacks challenges you to use your skills and creativity to address the global issue of &lt
column7: . Innovate, collaborate, and build impactful solutions that promote a healthier planet for all.&lt

column3: Your mission: Develop a project that drives positive environmental change. Whether you focus on climate action, resource management, or eco-friendly practices, the possibilities are limitless.&lt

column4: re looking for: We want to see innovative, tech-driven solutions that tackle pressing environmental challenges. The theme is open-ended, encouraging fresh ideas and bold thinking to protect and preserve our environment.&lt

column3: No matter your background or experience level, your passion for sustainability can spark real change.&lt

column7: and outshine the ordinary. The future of sustainability starts with you!&lt

column1: How unique and creative is the solution? Does the project introduce a new idea or a fresh approach to solving an environmental sustainability challenge? Is the project pushing the boundaries of technology integration for a sustainable future?

Does the project address a significant problem related to environmental sustainability? How practical and applicable is the solution to real-world issues? Can the solution be scaled or further developed for broader use?

How advanced and sophisticated is the technology used in the project? Is the project technically challenging or innovative in its application of relevant technologies? Does it demonstrate a deep understanding of the technical aspects?

How well is the project presented in the video demo? Is the documentation clear, concise, and detailed enough to understand the project’s purpose and technical details? Does the presentation effectively convey the project’s impact, value, and innovation?
,Outshine the ordinary at Eclipse Hacks! Join 50+ participants Nov 15-16 to create solutions for environmental sustainability. Prizes are growing! Be part of the impact!,

column3: One member from each team must signup through this &lt
Your complete project must be submitted via a public GitHub repository. Ensure that all code, documentation, and necessary files are included for judges to access and review.&lt
Include a clear and concise description of your project on Devpost, outlining its purpose, functionality, and how it addresses the theme of environmental sustainability.&lt
A short video (up to 3 minutes) demonstrating the key features of your project and how it works. This is your chance to showcase your innovation!&lt
Your repository must contain a well-structured README file that explains how to set up, run, and test your project. Include any necessary installation steps and usage instructions.&lt
List the names and roles of all team members involved in the project.&lt

column5: up to 4 participants, with a minimum of 2.&lt

column3: All projects must be original and created during the hackathon. Pre-existing code, projects, or submissions from previous events are not allowed.&lt
All projects must be submitted by the deadline specified on Devpost. Late submissions will not be accepted or judged.&lt
Participants are encouraged to use open-source libraries, APIs, and frameworks, but they must be properly credited. Plagiarism of code or content is strictly prohibited.&lt
The project must be submitted via a public GitHub repository. Ensure that all necessary files are included and the project is accessible for judges to review.&lt
Participants must adhere to respectful communication and collaboration. Harassment or discrimination of any kind will not be tolerated. Violators will be disqualified.&lt

Projects must align with the hackathon theme of environmental sustainability. The specific prompt will be announced during the event, but solutions should generally aim to address environmental challenges.&lt
Participants retain full ownership of their projects, including any intellectual property. However, Eclipse Hacks reserves the right to showcase and promote winning submissions.&lt
The hackathon is open to all students aged 13+. Participants must register through the official sign-up link prior to the event.&lt

column4: DR.​ Be respectful. Harassment and abuse are never tolerated. If you are in a situation that makes you uncomfortable at an MLH Member Event, if the event itself is creating an unsafe or inappropriate environment, or if interacting with an MLH representative or event organizer makes you uncomfortable, please report it using the procedures included in this document.&lt

column3: Major League Hacking (MLH) stands for inclusivity. We believe that every single person has the right to hack in a safe and welcoming environment.&lt

Harassment includes but is not limited to offensive verbal or written comments related to gender, age, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, social class, economic status, veteran status, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, harassing photography or recording, sustained disruption of talks or other events, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention. If what you’re doing is making someone feel uncomfortable, that counts as harassment and is enough reason to stop doing it.&lt
Participants asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.&lt

Sponsors, judges, mentors, volunteers, organizers, MLH staff, and anyone else at the event are also subject to the anti-harassment policy. In particular, attendees should not use sexualised images, activities, or other material both in their hacks and during the event. Booth staff (including volunteers) should not use sexualised clothing/uniforms/costumes, or otherwise create a sexualised environment.&lt

If a participant engages in harassing behavior, MLH may take any action it deems appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the event with no eligibility for reimbursement or refund of any type.&lt
If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact MLH using the reporting procedures defined below.&lt

MLH representatives will be happy to help participants contact campus security or local law enforcement, provide escorts, or otherwise assist those experiencing harassment to feel safe for the duration of the event. We value your attendance.&lt
We expect participants to follow these rules at all hackathon venues, online interactions in relation to the event, hackathon-related social events, and on hackathon supplied transportation.&lt

If you feel uncomfortable or think there may be a potential violation of the code of conduct, please report it immediately using one of the following methods. All reporters have the right to remain anonymous.&lt
By sending information to the general reporting line, your report will go to any or all of the MLH representatives listed below.&lt
If you are uncomfortable reporting your situation to one or more of these people or need to contact any of them directly in case of emergency, direct contact details are listed below.&lt

MLH reserves the right to revise, make exceptions to, or otherwise amend these policies in whole or in part. If you have any questions regarding these policies, please contact MLH by e-mail at​ hi@mlh.io​.&lt
The competition is just a part of the hackathon. To make the most out of the event, try something new, teach other people, and make new friends!&lt

column5: Happy Hacking from the MLH team!&lt

column8: Cascade Hacks is an in-person hackathon for all Calgary high school and middle school students, taking place on August 19th and 20th at the Calgary Central Library. This event is designed to be beginner-friendly, making it the perfect opportunity for hackathon newcomers to gain valuable hands-on experience before the school year.&lt

The hackathon will run for 24 hours, with food and drinks provided. To accommodate participants with varying levels of experience and skills, we offer both Hackathon and Ideathon streams for teams to choose from. The prompt will be revealed the day of the event.&lt

In addition to the main competition, there will be numerous opportunities for participants to engage in networking with peers, mentors, and event sponsors. While awaiting judges’ decisions, we will be hosting a series of mini workshops to give participants insight into what a future career in tech may look like.&amp

Cascade Hacks strives to create an inclusive space where students from all backgrounds can collaborate on impactful solutions, build their portfolios, and learn in a fast-paced environment, all while enjoying a fun and engaging experience.&lt

column3: More details regarding prizes will be released closer to the date of the event.&lt

column8: The event will be taking place at the Central Library in Downtown Calgary (800 3 St SE, Calgary, AB T2G 2E7). This central location aims to ensure easy access for participants all around Calgary.&lt

The opening ceremony and meals will be held in Room 3-16B on the library’s third floor. Once the hackathon kicks off, teams are welcome to work from any location. Additionally, private breakout rooms within the library will be assigned to teams on a first-come, first-served basis to collaborate in throughout the hackathon.&lt

column8: Participants are tasked with building an innovative and functional software project that aligns with the prompt provided on the day of the event. Teams should focus on identifying a problem, brainstorming potential solutions, and then rapidly developing a proof of concept or working prototype. Projects can vary widely, and can be anything from a mobile app to a 2D-multiplayer game. The essential requirement is to maintain a clear connection between the software and the prompt, addressing a specific problem identified by your team.&lt

In addition to programming the project, hackathon participants must also prepare a short presentation (no longer than 3 minutes) to deliver to the judges. This presentation should highlight the problem your team has identified, the solution developed, its relevance to the prompt, and its potential for positive impact. It is also recommended to include a segment detailing individual team member roles and dynamics, as collaboration will be evaluated. Presentations will be conducted individually, however winning teams will also be asked to give a short pitch of their product to the audience.&lt

After presenting to the judges, teams should conduct a short product demo and provide an explanation of how the software was built and what technology was used. Teams who are unable to complete their project are encouraged to present a Figma or another visual representation of the intended design and functionality during the product demo. Demonstrated planning of the design of the software, even without full implementation, may count towards points in the Design and User Experience category of the rubric.&lt

column5: Participants are tasked with developing a comprehensive proposal for a software product that addresses the given prompt. Teams should aim to identify a clear problem or need, conduct thorough research, and ideate potential solutions. While the actual creation of the product is not required, Ideathon project entries should feature well-thought-out plans for both implementation and business strategy. In place of being judged on Technical Execution, these projects will be evaluated on Feasibility and Marketability, necessitating thorough planning. &lt

During the judging period, teams must deliver a presentation on their product lasting no longer than 6 minutes. This presentation should cover the problem identified, the proposed product solution, plans for implementation, and strategies for reaching the target audience. It is also recommended to include a segment detailing individual team member roles and dynamics, as collaboration will be evaluated. &lt

Ideathon participants will also be expected to create a basic mockup of their product’s main design to be exhibited during or after the presentation. This mockup can be made using Figma, InVision, Canva, or another digital design tool, and will count towards the Design and User Experience category of the rubric.&lt

column8: Both streams must submit all finished work to Devpost by 11:45 AM on August 20th, with a 15-minute grace period. This includes the final product presentation for judges, as well as any files or photos of design mock-ups intended for display. Hackathon participants must also provide a link to the project’s source code, preferably hosted on GitHub.&lt

Submissions to Devpost must include completed project description sections, detailing the purpose and functionality of your project, the technologies used, and the challenges your team overcame. Additionally, it is recommended that participants fill out member roles after submission to contribute to the Collaboration section of the rubric.&lt
All teams are to consist of 2 to 4 participants. If you need help finding a team, please indicate this on the registration form and we’ll be happy to find one for you!&lt
This Hackathon is intended for high school students, but all students ages 13-18 are welcome to participate.&lt

column3: A Project must not have been developed, or derived from a Project developed, with financial or preferential support from the Sponsor or Administrator. Such Projects include, but are not limited to, those that received funding or investment for their development, were developed under contract, or received a commercial license, from the Sponsor or Administrator any time prior to the end of Hackathon Submission Period. The Sponsor, at their sole discretion, may disqualify a Project, if awarding a prize to the Project would create a real or apparent conflict of interest.&lt

Prior to the end of the Submission Period, you may save draft versions of your Submission on Devpost to your portfolio before submitting the submission materials to the Hackathon for evaluation. Once the Submission Period has ended, you may not make any changes or alterations to your Submission, but you may continue to update the Project in your Devpost portfolio.&lt

After the Submission Period. The Sponsor and Devpost may permit you to modify part of your Submission after the Submission Period for the purpose of adding, removing or replacing material that potentially infringes a third party mark or right, discloses personally identifiable information, or is otherwise inappropriate. The modified Submission must remain substantively the same as the original Submission with the only modification being what the Sponsor and Devpost permits. &lt

Eligible Submissions will be evaluated by a panel of judges selected by the Sponsor (the “Judges”). Judges may be employees of the Sponsor or third parties, may or may not be listed individually on the Hackathon Website, and may change before or during the Judging Period. Judging may take place in one or more rounds with one or more panels of Judges, at the discretion of the Sponsor. &lt

Stage One- The first stage will determine via pass/fail whether the ideas meet a baseline level of viability, in that the Project reasonably fits the theme and reasonably applies the required APIs/SDKs featured in the Hackathon.&lt
Stage Two- All Submissions that pass Stage One will be evaluated in Stage Two based on the following equally weighted criteria (the “Judging Criteria”):&lt
Entries will be judged on the following equally weighted criteria, and according to the sole and absolute discretion of the judges:&lt
How novel and innovative is the idea? Does it set out to do something completely different or at least improve existing models?&lt
What is the tech like? Does it have comprehensive and efficient features? Is the code understandable and usable by others? Is it designed to scale?&lt
What is the value proposition and how does it set out to differentiate itself? How will it capture value, new users and/or generate revenue? Is the project positioned to succeed?&lt
What is the user experience like? Is it clean and intuitive? How will you implement UX/UI?&lt
Is this something people would actually use and want? Will the idea have an impact on people, revolutionize some aspect of human life, or disrupt the status quo?&lt
Contribution to the Global Blockchain Ecosystem&lt
How does your idea increase global blockchain adoption, value for its users, and innovation in the field of Open Source technology? Does it welcome new users and help existing users?&lt

The scores from the Judges will determine the potential winners of the applicable prizes. The Entrant(s) that are eligible for a Prize, and whose Submissions earn the highest overall scores based on the applicable Judging Criteria, will become potential winners of that Prize.&lt
Stage 3- At least one member of each of the top three scoring projects for each track must present their project for the judges on a live Zoom/Google meets call on &lt

column15: First place projects will be determined on the following items: &lt

column3: Clearly articulate the problem or challenge that the application aims to solve.&lt
Explain the significance of this problem and why it matters.&lt
Present a high-level overview of the application.&lt
Explain how the application addresses the problem stated.&lt
Describe the technical architecture of the application.&lt
Highlight any unique technologies or methodologies used.&lt
Mention any challenges faced during development and how they were overcome.&lt
Provide a live demonstration of the application.&lt
Walk through key features and functionalities.&lt
Emphasize the user experience and interface.&lt
Discuss the target audience and potential market for the application.&lt
Explain the business model and how the application could be monetized or scaled.&lt
Outline the future development plans for the application.&lt
Mention any upcoming features or improvements.&lt
Prepare to answer questions from the judges and audience.&lt
Be ready to discuss technical details, market strategy, and any other relevant aspects.&lt

For each Prize listed below, if two or more Submissions are tied, the tied Submission with the highest score in the first applicable criterion listed above will be considered the higher scoring Submission. In the event any ties remain, this process will be repeated, as needed, by comparing the tied Submissions’ scores on the next applicable criterion. If two or more Submissions are tied on all applicable criteria, the panel of Judges will vote on the tied Submissions.&lt

Upon the successful completion of Stage 3 and securing a win in their respective track, participants will transition into the Milestone Program, which is exclusively sponsored by the official sponsor of that track (hereinafter referred to as the “Track Sponsor”). This next phase represents a critical development period wherein participants will work closely with the Track Sponsor to achieve predefined milestones over a designated period.&lt

The Milestone Program is meticulously designed to align with the specific track’s objectives, offering participants a structured framework of support, including but not limited to, targeted resources, strategic mentorship, and market entry assistance. The primary objective of this program is to foster continued growth and success, ensuring that participants’ projects can effectively scale and integrate within their respective markets, while also benefiting from potential partnerships and further development opportunities.&lt

Participants should refer to the table in Section 8. Prizes for comprehensive details regarding the specific milestones, unlock dates, and corresponding prizes associated with the program. It is important to note that, upon entering the Milestone Program, all communications, obligations, and interactions will be directly between the participants and the Track Sponsor. From this point forward, Devpost and GDA Capital will no longer be involved in the management or administration of the participant’s progression within the Milestone Program.&lt

Participants acknowledge and agree that the Track Sponsor assumes full responsibility for the execution and management of the Milestone Program, including the disbursement of prizes and the provision of support as outlined in the program. Once participants enter the Milestone Program, the disbursement of prizes is solely the responsibility of the Track Sponsor, with no involvement or liability on the part of GDA Capital or Devpost. The Track Sponsor reserves the right, in its sole discretion, to amend, modify, or terminate any aspect of the Milestone Program, including but not limited to the milestones, timelines, and prize structures, to ensure compliance with applicable laws and regulations, as well as to uphold the program’s integrity and objectives.&lt

By advancing into the Milestone Program, participants agree to adhere to all terms and conditions set forth by the Track Sponsor, and any disputes or claims arising out of or related to the Milestone Program shall be addressed directly with the Track Sponsor, with no recourse to GDA Capital or Devpost. This transition is intended to streamline the process and provide participants with direct access to the resources and expertise necessary to achieve their project’s full potential.&lt

All Submissions remain the intellectual property of the individuals or organizations that developed them. By submitting an entry, entrants agree that the Sponsor will have a fully paid, non-exclusive license to use such entry for judging the entry. Entrants agree that the Sponsor and Devpost shall have the right to promote the Submission and use the name, likeness, voice and image of all individuals contributing to a Submission, in any materials promoting or publicizing the Hackathon and its results, during the Hackathon Period and for three years thereafter.  Some Submission components may be displayed to the public. Other Submission materials may be viewed by the sponsor, Devpost, and judges for screening and evaluation. column9: VicHack is the largest Victorian student hackathon collaboration, brought to you by HackMelbourne, DSCUBED, MAC, MDN, and RISC. Spanning UniMelb, Monash, and RMIT, this hackathon is your ultimate hub for innovation, fun, and deep dives into the technical intricacies of various cutting-edge fields.&lt
We have four core streams for you to choose from, each offering a unique journey into groundbreaking technology:&lt

column7: Blockchain technology is set to revolutionize the way we build secure applications across industries such as finance, healthcare, and education.&lt
Data is ubiquitous, and harnessing it can unlock valuable insights. Dive into data science to learn how to capture and utilize data effectively.&lt
Machines are on the brink of autonomous thinking. Utilize AI to build intelligent applications and uncover unique discoveries.&lt
Handheld devices are integral to our daily lives. Learn how to develop powerful applications that can transform everyday activities.&lt
Attend the stream workshops to get a feel for each stream and decide which one aligns with your interests.&lt
Form your team, choose a stream, build an innovative project, and submit it to the hackathon.&lt
Join us on Friday, August 9th, to kick off the hackathon and gather all the essential information.&lt
On Saturday, August 10th, head to the University of Melbourne to start working on your project, meet new people, and win exciting prizes.&lt
Bring your friends to Monash University on Saturday, August 17th, for more fun and a chance to win exclusive prizes.&lt
Ensure your project is submitted by Sunday, August 18th, at 11 PM to compete for the main prize.&lt

Submitted miniapps can go live to our community of more than 20k users in the web app at &lt
column13: and also live on the iOS appstore!&lt

column3: All miniapp code is open source, so you can remix and learn from examples.&lt
You earn Seam Points when other users unlock your miniapps.&lt

Before creating a miniapp, you should join Seam! Creating a Seam account allows you to claim a username and profile that will be used as the author of the miniapp. More importantly though, it allows you to join a community of other builders, designers, and curators all building the future of social networking together.&lt

column9: , our step-by-step guide to get you started. Miniapps are small React components written in Typescript. If you have written JavaScript before, this will be a fun challenge. column3: The goal for this miniapp challenge is to create new, fun ways to share with your friends on Seam.&lt

Miniapps make posts. Users play with miniapps to create new art, music, or games, which then can be experienced by your friends. Miniapps live inside Seam, the super app, which acts as a constant contact book and platform for the feeds and groupchats that miniapps live inside of. Miniapps are creative tools that render their end product to a feed.&lt

A miniapp fundamentally has two steps. They start with the singleplayer mode, where someone enters their data, plays the game, or interacts with the app. The second mode is how it shows up in a feed, which is a typically the finished product of the creative process: the finished song, GIF, or highscore. Some quick examples:&lt
Artistic miniapps first allow artists to draw on a canvas, and then post their watercolor. Yes, Microsoft Paint is basically a miniapp.&lt
Commerce miniapps first allow a seller to decide what to sell and how to make the post look, and then allows users to buy with one tap.&lt
Game miniapps first allow friends to play the game, and then allows them to compete by posting their highscores.&lt
Utility miniapps take the most arcane 3D image filetypes, and then render them properly in the feed.&lt
The options for miniapps are endless — see the examples that already exist on &lt

column7: A hackathon is a time-bound event, usually spanning from 24 to 48 hours, where individuals or teams collaborate intensively to create innovative solutions, most often related to software or technology.&lt

During a hackathon, participants are typically presented with a problem or theme and are tasked to come up with a creative and functional solution. This can involve coding, design, strategizing, and more.&lt

Hackathons offer a unique platform for learning and networking. They bring together people with various skills - coders, designers, entrepreneurs, etc. - to work together, learn from each other, and potentially turn ideas into reality.&lt

column14: Why You Should Join A Hackathon!&lt

column9: Hackathons offer a hands-on experience that goes beyond traditional classroom learning. It&#39
column10: s an opportunity to work on a real project, under time pressure, with a team - much like you would in a professional setting.&lt

column9: These events are typically attended by individuals from diverse backgrounds, from fellow students to industry professionals and potential employers. This can be a great chance to make connections that could help in your future career.&lt
Hackathons are a fantastic way to develop and refine a broad range of skills, including coding, problem-solving, teamwork, and communication.&lt
Hackathons are all about innovation. They encourage you to think outside the box, develop unique solutions to problems, and push the boundaries of technology.&lt

column3: We are committed to providing a welcoming, inclusive, and safe environment for all participants at the Techstars Startup Weekend - PAI Palooza - Seattle. This Code of Conduct is based on the guidelines provided by the &lt
column9: and reflects our commitment to a respectful and collaborative atmosphere.&lt

column3: Treat everyone with respect, kindness, and consideration. Disrespectful, discriminatory, or harassing behavior will not be tolerated.&lt

Celebrate diversity and foster an inclusive environment. All participants should feel valued regardless of gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or technology choices.&lt
Understand that we may all have different perspectives. Critique ideas, not people. Avoid disruptive behavior that could impede the event’s activities or enjoyment for others.&lt
Support and encourage each other. Share knowledge and resources freely. Collaboration is key to innovation and success.&lt
Act with integrity and honesty. Do not misrepresent yourself or your work. Give proper credit for ideas and contributions.&lt
Respect the privacy and confidentiality of others. Do not share personal information or sensitive data without consent.&lt
Unacceptable behaviors include, but are not limited to:&lt
Harassment, intimidation, or discrimination in any form.&lt
Offensive verbal or written comments related to gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or technology choices.&lt
Sustained disruption of talks, presentations, or other events.&lt
Advocating for, or encouraging, any of the above behavior.&lt

Anyone asked to stop unacceptable behavior is expected to comply immediately. If a participant engages in unacceptable behavior, the organizers may take any action deemed appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the event without a refund.&lt
If you are subjected to unacceptable behavior or witness someone else being harassed, please report it as soon as possible. You can report issues to any event organizer or staff member.&lt

column5: All reports will be handled with discretion and confidentiality.&lt

These challenges range anywhere from not having a sustainable website that helps them manage their operations, to looking for new software to simplify their day-to-day procedures. This year&#x27
column4: s theme, Code4Good, challenges participants to think critically about specific problems that someone in their community or a small business is facing and masterfully develops a solution that targets that issue. TerraHacks is a 36-hour hackathon open to everyone of all skill levels to come collaborate on projects and work together to create solutions to real-world problems. TerraHacks 2024 is held on Toronto Metropolitan University Campus in Downtown Toronto from August 2nd to August 4th. From various mini-events, networking opportunities with sponsors and peers, to workshops and mentorship, TerraHacks aims to offer a memorable experience for all its participants in its first year.&lt

TerraHacks aims to bridge the gap between academia and the industry, while raising awareness about various environmental issues facing our world today. We aim to create a space for students from diverse backgrounds to bring their ideas together in order to create an impactful solution, build their portfolio, and learn in fast-paced environment, all while offering a fun experience for all our participants.&lt

column3: We are committed to providing a welcoming, inclusive, and safe environment for all participants at the Techstars Startup Weekend - PAI Palooza - Denver. This Code of Conduct is based on the guidelines provided by the &lt
column9: and reflects our commitment to a respectful and collaborative atmosphere.&lt

column3: Treat everyone with respect, kindness, and consideration. Disrespectful, discriminatory, or harassing behavior will not be tolerated.&lt

Celebrate diversity and foster an inclusive environment. All participants should feel valued regardless of gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or technology choices.&lt
Understand that we may all have different perspectives. Critique ideas, not people. Avoid disruptive behavior that could impede the event’s activities or enjoyment for others.&lt
Support and encourage each other. Share knowledge and resources freely. Collaboration is key to innovation and success.&lt
Act with integrity and honesty. Do not misrepresent yourself or your work. Give proper credit for ideas and contributions.&lt
Respect the privacy and confidentiality of others. Do not share personal information or sensitive data without consent.&lt
Unacceptable behaviors include, but are not limited to:&lt
Harassment, intimidation, or discrimination in any form.&lt
Offensive verbal or written comments related to gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or technology choices.&lt
Sustained disruption of talks, presentations, or other events.&lt
Advocating for, or encouraging, any of the above behavior.&lt

Anyone asked to stop unacceptable behavior is expected to comply immediately. If a participant engages in unacceptable behavior, the organizers may take any action deemed appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the event without a refund.&lt
If you are subjected to unacceptable behavior or witness someone else being harassed, please report it as soon as possible. You can report issues to any event organizer or staff member.&lt

column5: All reports will be handled with discretion and confidentiality.&lt
The organizing team will take all reports seriously and investigate them promptly. We are committed to taking appropriate action to ensure a safe and welcoming environment for all participants.&lt

column3: MEGA is a dynamic and diverse coalition of high school and college students from around the world, attending institutions such as the University of Pennsylvania, UC Berkeley, University of Chicago, Duke University, Georgia Institute of Technology, The University of Glasgow, Rutgers Preparatory School, Milton Academy, The Hun School of Princeton, The Lawrenceville School, and many more. With a shared commitment to fostering sustainable development and promoting global welfare, MEGA is proud to announce its upcoming hackathon, MEGA Hackathon 2024, which is slated to take place online on Saturday, July 27, 2024, and Sunday, July 28, 2024. The objective of this hackathon will be to apply computer science or artificial intelligence to improve the process of education. This can be completed in the form of a business plan, game, application, or website.&lt

column6: a safe space where people from different backgrounds can come together to learn and craft. As such, we do not tolerate harassment, discrimination or abuse of any kind, whatsoever. &lt

column5: Harassment includes, but is not limited to, offensive verbal or written comments or imagery related to gender identity and expression, age, sexual orientation, disability, personal appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, religion (or lack thereof), social class, economic status, veteran status, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, harassing photography or recording, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention. Any attendees at StarterHacks Event-related Booths (including volunteers, partners and sponsors) should not use sexualised clothing/uniforms/costumes, or otherwise create a sexualised environment. &lt

If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please reach out to a StarterHacks organizer via Discord or one of the alternative contact methods listed at the end of the document with a description of the incident, when and where it happened, and any other details you feel comfortable disclosing. &lt

StarterHacks representatives take your safety and well being seriously and will take any necessary procedures to help participants contact the venue’s security or local law enforcement, provide escorts, or otherwise assist those experiencing harassment to feel safe for the duration of the event. We value your attendance. &lt
We expect participants to follow these rules at all StarterHacks Events venues, online interactions in relation to the Events, and all StarterHacks social events. &lt

If you feel uncomfortable or think there may be a potential violation of the Code of Conduct, please report it immediately using one of the following methods. All reporters have the right to remain anonymous. &lt
By sending information to the general reporting line, your report will go to your StarterHacks Events team. &lt

If you believe you are in an emergency situation, please contact the authorities at 911 immediately and then follow the discord instructions under reporting procedures. &lt

If the Project includes software that runs on proprietary or third party hardware that is not widely available to the public, including software running on devices or wearable technology other than smartphones, tablets, or desktop computers, the Sponsor and/or Administrator reserve the right, at their sole discretion, to require the Entrant to provide physical access to the Project hardware upon request.  &lt

All Submission materials must be in English or, if not in English, the Entrant must provide an English translation of the demonstration video, text description, and testing instructions as well as all other materials submitted. &lt

If a team or organization is entering the Hackathon, they must appoint and authorize one individual (the “Representative”) to represent, act, and enter a Submission, on their behalf. The Representative must meet the eligibility requirements above. By entering a Submission on the Hackathon Website on behalf of a team or organization you represent and warrant that you are the Representative authorized to act on behalf of your team or organization.&lt

An Entrant may submit a Submission that includes the use of open source software or hardware, provided the Entrant complies with applicable open source licenses and, as part of the Submission, creates software that enhances and builds upon the features and functionality included in the underlying open source product. column24: How novel and innovative is the idea? Does it set out to do something unique or at least improve existing models?&lt

column1: This criteria assesses the overall quality of your HTML and CSS code. Judges will look for well-structured, clean, and semantically meaningful code. Proper indentation, commenting, and organization will be essential.

This category focuses on the aesthetic appeal and user-friendliness of your web project. Judges will consider factors such as layout, color schemes, typography, and responsive design. A well-designed and visually engaging project will score higher.

This criterion assesses the functionality and interactivity of your web application. Judges will look for features like responsive navigation, interactive elements(e.g.,buttons,forms)and any JavaScript or CSS animations that enhance the user experience.

This category evaluates how well your project adapts to different screen sizes and devices. Judges will consider whether your design is mobile-friendly, how elements scale, and if there are any issues with responsiveness.

This criterion rewards innovative and creative elements in your project. Judges will look for unique design concepts, creative use of HTML and CSS, and any special features that set your project apart from the rest.
Judges will assess whether your project adheres to web development standards and best practices. This includes valid HTML and CSS, proper use of tags, and efficient code.
Judges will assess the performance of your project. This includes loading times, page speed, and overall optimization. A faster, more efficient project will receive a higher score.

This category considers how effectively you present and communicate your project to the judges. This includes the clarity of your project demonstration, the completeness of your presentation, and your ability to explain design and coding choices.

column3: Participants must be aged 13-21 years old.&lt
Open to individuals or teams of up to 5 members.&lt
Projects must address the theme of bridging the technology gap in education. Solutions should be innovative, practical, and aimed at empowering under-resourced communities.&lt
Innovation: Evaluate the originality and creativity of the solution presented. Look for innovative approaches and unique ideas that demonstrate out-of-the-box thinking.&lt

Impact: Assess the potential impact and scalability of the solution. Consider how effectively the solution addresses the problem statement and its potential to make a positive difference in the intended context.&lt

Feasibility: Determine the practicality and implementability of the solution. Evaluate whether the solution can be realistically developed and deployed, considering available resources and constraints.&lt
Technical Quality: Examine the technical execution of the project. Review the quality of the code, the efficiency of the solution, and the thoroughness of the documentation.&lt

Presentation: Evaluate the clarity and effectiveness of the project presentation. Consider the quality of the video demonstration, the comprehensiveness of the documentation, and how well the project is communicated overall.&lt
Submissions will be evaluated by a panel of judges, including industry experts, educators, and TechLit representatives.&lt
Each judge will score the projects based on the criteria outlined above.&lt
Scores from all judges will be averaged to determine the top projects.&lt
Winners will be selected based on the highest average scores. In the event of a tie, the panel of judges will deliberate to select the final winners.&lt
Winners will be announced at the closing ceremony of the hackathon.&lt
Winners will also be notified via email and announced on the TechLit website and social media channels.&lt
Participants will receive feedback from the judges on their submissions, highlighting strengths and areas for improvement.&lt

column5: A detailed rubric will be used to evaluate your presentations and demos, ensuring a fair and transparent review process. This rubric will be shared with participants at a later stage. Here’s a sneak peek at the key criteria:&lt

column8: Originality: How unique and innovative is the idea compared to existing solutions?&lt
Creativity: How creatively is the digital ID system utilized in the proposed solution?&lt
Technical Feasibility: Can the solution be realistically developed with the current technology stack and within the provided time frame?&lt
Operational Feasibility: Can the solution be implemented and maintained effectively in the targeted regions?&lt
Scalability: Can the solution be scaled to a larger population or different regions with minimal changes?&lt
Adaptability: Can the solution be adapted to other contexts or use cases?&lt
Long-term Viability: Is the solution sustainable in the long run, both in terms of technical maintenance and financial viability?&lt
Resource Utilization: How efficiently does the solution use resources such as data, infrastructure, and personnel?&lt
Problem Addressed: Does the idea address a significant problem or challenge specific to Africa as a whole, or the participants’ region?&lt

column10: [10%] Security and Privacy friendly / Digital rights&lt

column8: Data Security: How well does the solution protect sensitive user data?&lt
Privacy Protection: Does the solution comply with privacy laws and best practices to ensure user privacy while empowering users over their personal information?&lt
Transparency: Is the solution transparent in its operations and data handling practices?&lt

column9: s accuracy: Is the documentation clear, verifiable, accurate, detailed, and well-organized?&lt

column8: Clarity of Idea Submission: Is the idea submission well-written, coherent, and easy to understand?&lt
Ethical Use: Does the solution consider ethical implications, such as avoiding discrimination and ensuring fairness and inclusivity?&lt
Accessibility: Does the solution consider and accommodate users with disabilities or those with limited access to technology?&lt
Impact Potential: How impactful is the proposed solution for the African population? Consider potential reach and depth of impact.&lt
Community Benefits: How does the solution benefit the local community?&lt

Engagement Strategy: How does the solution plan to engage with and involve the community in its implementation and use? The ideal use case would clearly identify the target communities and explain their involvement, part to play and ways to engage with the team when needed (biometric registrations, awareness, assistance and support, etc). &lt

column7: A selection committee will review idea submissions based on the rubric and select the most promising projects to advance.&lt
Judges will evaluate the functionality, presentation and code of the prototypes of best 4-5 teams to the rubric to select finalists.&lt
Finalists will present their projects live, and judges will select the winners based on the rubric criteria.&lt

column3: What to Build: anything within our technolgical world!&lt

Ideation: Brainstorm and come up with an idea for a project that utilizes technology. Consider current trends, pain points, and opportunities for innovation. Your project can be an app, website, hardware device, software tool, game, or any other technology-based solution.&lt

Development: Use the tools and resources available to start building your project. You may choose to code from scratch, use pre-built platforms, or leverage existing APIs and libraries. Take advantage of online tutorials, documentation, and community support to help guide you along the way.&lt

Testing: Regularly test your project throughout development to ensure everything works as expected. Identify bugs and issues early on and address them promptly. Seek feedback from others and iterate on your design until it meets your standards.&lt

Presentation: Prepare a presentation to showcase your project to judges and attendees. Highlight the key features and benefits, explain the technical implementation, and discuss any challenges encountered during development. Demonstrate your passion and enthusiasm for the project, and be prepared to answer questions about your work.&lt

Reflection: After the event, take time to reflect on your experience and learnings. Think about ways to improve your project, and consider future applications for the technology you developed. Share your successes and failures with others to inspire continued learning and growth.&lt

column8: Submit during the alloted time slot (Jul 19th 12:00 AM UTC - Jul 21st 11:59 PM UTC) to &lt

In order to be eligible for the novice prize, you must specify that you are new to making games (if this is your first game jam or you have almost never made a game in whatever genre you chose before).&lt
To be eligible for a prize, you must provide an adequate explanation for how your game fits the theme when submitting your game.&lt

Any digital project that is not malware may be submitted. Keep in mind, however, that the judging criteria may limit your success if you do not submit a game that fits the theme announced at the beginning of the jam. &lt

All submissions must be developed during the alloted time slot mentioned above. However, you are free to use any assets (music, 3d models, etc.) and tools (game engines, graphic design programs, etc.) that you made yourself or are given permission to use by the creators, such as through a creative commons license, an open-source license, or a purchase. &lt
Participants may work alone, or form teams of up to 4 members in order to work on their submission. Participants can be in multiple teams, but cannot win prizes more than once per jam.&lt

The Cupertino Game Development Club reserves the right to not consider any uploaded games for prizes if the content is offensive or unsuitable. This includes but is not limited to: games with harmful or prejudicial themes related to gender, sexual orientation, age, ability, appearance, ethnicity, national origin, citizenship, socioeconomic status, or religion. &lt
You may use any engines or tools at your disposal except for generative AI. No AI art, code, music, or any other assets is allowed.&lt
Participants who do not adhere to the rules above may have their submission canceled. &lt

For prizes in each category (novice, intermediate, and advanced), each game submitted to the MelonJam game jam will be given a score out of 10 for each judging criterion. These scores will then be summed. The game with the highest score in its category will be the winner of that division&#x27
column9: s prize. If there are multiple games with the highest score, they will be given a holistic review by the judges, who will then come to a joint decision about which project is the winner in that category out of all of the games with the highest score.&lt

column4: DR.​ Be respectful. Harassment and abuse are never tolerated. If you are in a situation that makes you uncomfortable at an MLH Member Event, if the event itself is creating an unsafe or inappropriate environment, or if interacting with an MLH representative or event organizer makes you uncomfortable, please report it using the procedures included in this document.&lt

column3: Major League Hacking (MLH) stands for inclusivity. We believe that every single person has the right to hack in a safe and welcoming environment.&lt

Harassment includes but is not limited to offensive verbal or written comments related to gender, age, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, social class, economic status, veteran status, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, harassing photography or recording, sustained disruption of talks or other events, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention. If what you’re doing is making someone feel uncomfortable, that counts as harassment and is enough reason to stop doing it.&lt
Participants asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.&lt

Sponsors, judges, mentors, volunteers, organizers, MLH staff, and anyone else at the event are also subject to the anti-harassment policy. In particular, attendees should not use sexualised images, activities, or other material both in their hacks and during the event. Booth staff (including volunteers) should not use sexualised clothing/uniforms/costumes, or otherwise create a sexualised environment.&lt

If a participant engages in harassing behavior, MLH may take any action it deems appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the event with no eligibility for reimbursement or refund of any type.&lt
If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact MLH using the reporting procedures defined below.&lt

MLH representatives will be happy to help participants contact campus security or local law enforcement, provide escorts, or otherwise assist those experiencing harassment to feel safe for the duration of the event. We value your attendance.&lt
We expect participants to follow these rules at all hackathon venues, online interactions in relation to the event, hackathon-related social events, and on hackathon supplied transportation.&lt

If you feel uncomfortable or think there may be a potential violation of the code of conduct, please report it immediately using one of the following methods. All reporters have the right to remain anonymous.&lt
By sending information to the general reporting line, your report will go to any or all of the MLH representatives listed below.&lt
If you are uncomfortable reporting your situation to one or more of these people or need to contact any of them directly in case of emergency, direct contact details are listed below.&lt
MLH reserves the right to revise, make exceptions to, or otherwise amend these policies in whole or in part. If you have any questions regarding these policies, please contact MLH by e-mail at​ &lt
The competition is just a part of the hackathon. To make the most out of the event, try something new, teach other people, and make new friends!&lt
Happy Hacking from the MLH team!&lt
If this is your first hackathon or if you want to learn a new skill, there are tons of resources available this weekend to aid your hackathon experience.&lt

column3: The Hack 7 Days Tezos India x CU Hackathon is a week-long challenge aimed at providing practical exposure to college students in India who are interested in blockchain development. The hackathon is being held in collaboration with various Tezos Clubs set up in different colleges and universities across India.&lt

With a week long plan of workshops that will cover the basics of blockchain, introduction to Tezos, Etherlink, Tezos as a protocol, running a node of Tezos, writing a tezos contract, introducing the tools for the development of tezos, and exploring possibilities in the Tezos Ecosystem. You can also refer to the resources provided in the previous prompts, such as the Getting started with Tezos Playlist, Smart Contract building using SmartPY guide, Building frontend for Smart contracts using Taquito.js guide, Token standards on Tezos guide, Fractionalization NFTS and Defi guide, and Building Dynamic NFTs using Revise guide.&lt
column5: You can also use Etherlink to build and deploy your EVM based projects on Tezos .&lt

,Getting started with blockchain development using Tezos and Etherlink blockchain,

column3: You can build a decentralized application (DApp) on the Tezos or Etherlink blockchain platform. The DApp can be related to any field such as finance, gaming, or social media, among others. You can also incorporate non-fungible tokens (NFTs) and explore their various use cases.&lt

To participate in the hackathon, you need to submit a working website / DApp built on the Tezos or Etherlink blockchain. The DApp should be accompanied by a detailed project report and documentation that outlines its features, functionalities, and implementation details.&lt
All college / University students are eligible for participating in hackathon&lt

The project should be built using the Tezos or Etherlink blockchain platform and should be original and innovative. The DApp should be functional, user-friendly, and secure. The project report should include a detailed description of the DApp, its features, functionalities, and implementation details. The submission should also include a video demo of the DApp.&lt

The prizes for the hackathon include 8,000 INR for the best DApp built on Tezos, 6000 INR for the first runner up DApp built on Tezos, 4000 INR for the second runner up DApp built on Tezos grant opportunities up to 4 Lakh INR for the best DApp built on Tezos, certificates to all the participants who submit their project, and Tezos goodies to all the participants who submit their projects.&lt

The submissions will be evaluated based on various criteria such as creativity, originality, functionality, user experience, security, and scalability. The winners will be selected by a panel of judges based on the above criteria. The decision of the judges will be final and binding&lt

Regardless of the amount of experience you may have, don&#39
column4: t be shy to join our hackathon!&lt

column1: ,Work with Ingenium STEM and fulfill our goal to provide free and accessible STEM education to learners of all ages.,

column3: For the Ingenium STEM Summer Hacks 2.0, participants are encouraged to create innovative and impactful projects that address various aspects of social good. Your project can take any form as long as it aims to make a positive difference in society. Here are some ideas to get you started:&lt
AI-Powered Community Support Platform: Develop a platform leveraging AI to provide resources, support, and connectivity within communities.&lt
Intelligent Tutoring System: Create an AI-driven tutoring system that offers personalized learning experiences and helps students improve their academic performance.&lt
Sustainable Living Recommendation Engine: Build a recommendation engine that suggests sustainable living practices to individuals and households based on their lifestyle and preferences.&lt
Healthcare Predictive Analytics: Design a predictive analytics tool to help healthcare providers anticipate and prevent health issues, improving patient outcomes.&lt
Disaster Response AI Assistant: Develop an AI assistant to aid in disaster response efforts, providing real-time information, coordination, and support to affected individuals and responders.&lt
Inclusive Social Platform with Sentiment Analysis: Create a social platform that promotes inclusivity and uses sentiment analysis to detect and mitigate harmful content.&lt
Mental Health Monitoring and Support System: Build a system that monitors mental health indicators and provides timely support and resources to individuals in need.&lt
Civic Engagement Chatbot: Design a chatbot to encourage civic engagement, educate users on civic duties, and facilitate participation in community initiatives.&lt
Elderly Care AI Companion: Develop an AI companion to assist elderly individuals with daily tasks, provide companionship, and ensure their safety and well-being.&lt
AI-Driven Local Business Support System: Create a system that uses AI to support local businesses, offering insights, resources, and tools to help them thrive.&lt
Remember, your project should leverage technology to solve real-world problems and create a tangible impact on society.&lt

column3: For your submission to the Ingenium STEM Summer Hacks 2.0, please ensure you include the following:&lt

Share a link to your GitHub repository containing all the source code, documentation, and any other relevant materials. Ensure your code is well-documented to help judges understand your implementation.&lt
Include a README file with a clear description of your project, the problem it addresses, the solution, and the impact it aims to make. Provide setup and usage instructions.&lt

If your project is a no-code solution, provide a comprehensive Google Docs file detailing your project. This should include the problem statement, your solution, the impact, and how it addresses the topic of social good.&lt
Include screenshots, diagrams, and any other relevant materials to effectively convey your project&#x27

If your project is deployed and available online, provide a link to the live project. Use platforms like Vercel, Heroku, GitHub Pages, or any other hosting service to make your project accessible for the judges to view and interact with.&lt

You may include a video (up to 3 minutes) demonstrating your project. This video should walk through your project, highlighting its features, functionality, and user interface. Mention the technologies used and how it addresses the topic of social good.&lt
Upload the video to a platform like YouTube or Vimeo and provide the link in your submission.&lt

Make sure your submission is well-organized and easy to navigate. Clear and thorough documentation will help judges understand and evaluate your project effectively. Good luck, and we look forward to seeing your innovative solutions for social good!&lt
Hackathon Start: July 11th, 2024 at 12:00 AM EST&lt
Hackathon End: September 11th, 2024 at 12:00 AM EST&lt
Competitors must be above the age of 13!&lt

column3: Submissions for the Ingenium STEM Summer Hacks 2.0 will be evaluated based on several key criteria to determine the winners. Judges will assess each project on its innovation, impact, and relevance to social good. Technical complexity and the quality of implementation will also play significant roles in the evaluation process. Creativity and originality in addressing the chosen social issue will be highly valued. Additionally, the clarity and comprehensiveness of the project&#x27
column4: s documentation, as well as the effectiveness of the demonstration (if provided), will influence the final decision. Projects that are well-documented, user-friendly, and demonstrate a clear and tangible benefit to society are more likely to stand out. Winners will be selected based on their overall score across these criteria, with special attention given to projects that show the potential for real-world application and scalability.&lt
