column8: Garuda Hacks values inclusion and equal opportunity for all our participants. A part of that is creating a safe and welcoming environment for fellow participants, committee members, and sponsors.  In line with these values and more, all hackathon participants and staff members are expected to abide by our code of conduct, including, but not limited to the following:&lt
Please be respectful of other participants and staff members. In fact, use Garuda Hacks as an opportunity to get to know fellow teammates, and even other participants!&lt

Participating in discrimination and or harassment of any kind will result in immediate disqualification and removal from the venue. This includes, but is not limited to, discrimination and or harassment stemming from one’s gender, age, race or ethnic identity, religion, sexual orientation, ability, and or political beliefs. &lt
If you or another participant sees or experiences discrimination and or harassment of any kind, please report it to a Garuda Hacks staff member. &lt

column8: All participants are expected to maintain decorum throughout the event. Additionally, please be mindful of quiet hours. Participants will be expected to code in the allocated premises if they plan to continue working past 11 P.M.. Anyone found to be in violation of this rule faces penalization and potential removal from the venue.&lt

Any offensive or violent displays (physical or verbal) to other participants, staff members, and or judges will lead to immediate disqualification and removal from the event. Furthermore, we may escalate the issue to our event host and/or the relevant authorities if necessary.  &lt

Please clean up after yourself and respect common spaces, as well as spaces allotted to you and your team. Throw away any trash, wipe up any messes, etc. Participating in any property destruction may lead to removal from the venue and &lt

Participating in any crime in and around the venue will lead to removal from the venue and immediate disqualification. This includes, but is not limited to, petty theft, larceny, assault, battery, etc. &lt

Consumption and possession of controlled substances during and around the event is strictly prohibited and will lead to immediate removal from the venue and potential disqualification. This includes, but is not limited to: Alcohol, illicit drugs, cigarettes, e-cigarettes (Juul, vape, etc.), as well as drug paraphernalia. &lt
Sexual activity is strictly prohibited within the premises of our event. &lt
For the safety of you and those around you, please refrain from bringing unregistered individuals into the event. Infractions of this rule may result in penalization. &lt
Please only enter sleeping pods assigned to your group. Anyone found to be in violation of this rule will be asked to leave the area and potentially face disqualification.&lt
Garuda Hacks does not assume responsibility for any lost possessions or items throughout the event. Therefore, all participants are encouraged to maintain their own belongings. &lt
Garuda Hacks reserves the right to remove any participant(s) from the event at any time. &lt
If it’s helpful, think of our code of conduct as a list of “do-nots”. Garuda Hacks also has some general guidelines. Treat them as a list of “dos”!&lt
Teams can register up to 4  members. &lt
Staff members are expected to not participate in the hackathon itself in any way. &lt
Teams are allotted 36 hours for their project. The hacking period will begin from &lt

column8: In addition to restricting plagiarism, teams are allowed to only use content created during the Hackathon itself. Prior content— whether this be ideas, code, etc— should not be used during the event. We check participants’ code to confirm that they abide by this rule.&lt
During registration, participants will be asked to present their identification. Please come prepared to the event with the proper documentation, or you may be unable to register. &lt
We want Garuda hacks to be an inclusive place! If you have any feedback or want to see something from the team, let us know!&lt

While we do not maintain strict clothing guidelines and we want our participants to be as comfortable as possible, Garuda Hacks participants are expected to maintain appropriate attire throughout the event. Please dress comfortably but also appropriately!&lt

column3: Welcome to the Bay Area Hackathon! An extraordinary event that stretches from the brisk beginnings of July 7, 2024, to the warm embrace of Aug 26, 2024. Nestled in the heart of innovation and technology, this hackathon is not just an event
column5: s a journey of creativity, learning, and groundbreaking development. Over the span of three months, we invite developers, designers, innovators, and dreamers from all corners to come together and transform their visions into reality.&lt

column3: What Makes the Bay Area Hackathon Special?&lt

Extended Timeline: Unlike traditional hackathons that last for a few days, our summer-long hackathon provides participants with the unique opportunity to deeply dive into their projects. This extended period allows for thorough research, development, testing, and refinement of ideas, ensuring that the final products are not just innovative but polished and practical.&lt

Hybrid Model: Embracing the best of both worlds, the Tri Valley Summer Long Hackathon offers a hybrid model where participants can choose to collaborate virtually from anywhere in the world or join in-person meetups and workshops in the Tri Valley area. This flexibility ensures that no matter where you are, you can be a part of this extraordinary event.&lt

Mentorship and Workshops: Throughout the hackathon, participants will have access to a wealth of resources including mentorship from industry leaders, workshops on the latest technologies and methodologies, and webinars on various aspects of product development and entrepreneurship. This supportive environment is designed to foster learning and growth, making it perfect for both seasoned professionals and those new to the hackathon scene.&lt

Diverse Themes and Challenges: The hackathon features a wide range of themes and challenges across various domains such as healthcare, education, environmental sustainability, and social justice. This diversity encourages participants to think creatively and work on projects that can make a real difference in the world.&lt

Community and Networking: By joining the Tri Valley Summer Long Hackathon, you become part of a vibrant community of like-minded individuals. The extended timeframe allows for meaningful connections, collaborations, and friendships that go beyond the hackathon itself.&lt

column4: re looking to push the boundaries of technology, solve real-world problems, or simply learn and grow with a community of innovators, the Tri Valley Summer Long Hackathon is the place to be. With its unique format, supportive environment, and endless possibilities, this hackathon promises to be an unforgettable experience. Let&#39
column5: s innovate, inspire, and impact the world together this summer!&lt

column3: For the Bay Area Hackathon, we invite you to build solutions that push the boundaries of technology and creativity. Your project can fall under any of the following broad themes:&lt
Healthcare Innovation: Develop solutions that can improve patient care, streamline healthcare processes, or increase accessibility to medical services.&lt
Educational Technologies: Create tools or platforms that enhance learning experiences, provide personalized education, or make education more accessible to underserved communities.&lt
Environmental Sustainability: Work on projects that promote environmental health, from reducing carbon footprints to improving renewable energy sources.&lt
Social Justice and Equality: Build applications or platforms that address issues of inequality, promote social justice, or aid in creating more inclusive communities.&lt
Open Category: If your project doesn&#x27
column4: t fit into the above categories, don&#x27

column3: Your project should be original, innovative, and capable of demonstrating a clear use case. It should utilize technology to solve a problem, fill a gap, or create a new opportunity that could benefit individuals, communities, or society at large.&lt
To ensure your submission is complete and stands out, please include the following on Devpost:&lt

Project Overview: A clear and concise description of your project, including the problem it addresses, the solution you propose, and the impact it could have. Highlight what makes your project innovative and necessary.&lt

Demo Video: Submit a video (no longer than 4 minutes) that demonstrates your project in action and walks viewers through the main features and functionalities. The video should also explain the problem, your solution, and the potential impact. Make sure the video is accessible (e.g., via YouTube or Vimeo) to the judges and the public.&lt

Technical Details: Provide a detailed explanation of the technologies used in your project, the architecture, and how it works. Include any technical challenges you overcame and how you addressed them.&lt
Code Repository: Include a link to a public code repository (e.g., GitHub) with your project&#x27

column3: Rules for DiverseHack by DiverseYouth Hackathon (DATES TBD):&lt
DiverseHack by DiverseYouth is open to participants of all ages, backgrounds, and skill levels, but it is primarily designed for beginner to intermediate coders.&lt
Participants under the age of 18 must have parental or guardian consent to participate.&lt
Teams can consist of 1 to 4 members. Each team member should meet the eligibility criteria.&lt
All submissions must be the original work of the participating teams. Plagiarism or the use of pre-existing solutions without proper attribution will result in disqualification.&lt
Projects should align with the hackathon theme of education and should aim to address challenges or enhance learning experiences in some way.&lt
While not mandatory, participants are encouraged to open-source their projects to promote knowledge sharing and collaboration within the coding community.&lt
Submissions must be completed and submitted by X (midnight), which is the official end time of the hackathon. Late submissions will not be accepted.&lt
Projects will be evaluated based on creativity, technical complexity, potential impact on education, and presentation quality.&lt

Participants retain intellectual property rights for their projects. However, by participating in DiverseHack by DiverseYouth, you grant the organizers the right to use your project for promotional and educational purposes.&lt
The organizers reserve the right to disqualify any project or participant that violates the rules or engages in unethical behavior.&lt
Participants must comply with all applicable laws and regulations during the hackathon.&lt
The organizers reserve the right to make changes to the rules and guidelines as needed, with any updates communicated to participants.&lt
Our Discord Server features a wide variety of mentors and tutors for you to work with if you have any questions during the hackathon.&lt

column4: DR.​ Be respectful. Harassment and abuse are never tolerated. If you are in a situation that makes you uncomfortable at an MLH Member Event, if the event itself is creating an unsafe or inappropriate environment, or if interacting with an MLH representative or event organizer makes you uncomfortable, please report it using the procedures included in this document.&lt

column3: Major League Hacking (MLH) stands for inclusivity. We believe that every single person has the right to hack in a safe and welcoming environment.&lt

Harassment includes but is not limited to offensive verbal or written comments related to gender, age, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, social class, economic status, veteran status, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, harassing photography or recording, sustained disruption of talks or other events, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention. If what you’re doing is making someone feel uncomfortable, that counts as harassment and is enough reason to stop doing it.&lt
Participants asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.&lt

Sponsors, judges, mentors, volunteers, organizers, MLH staff, and anyone else at the event are also subject to the anti-harassment policy. In particular, attendees should not use sexualised images, activities, or other material both in their hacks and during the event. Booth staff (including volunteers) should not use sexualised clothing/uniforms/costumes, or otherwise create a sexualised environment.&lt

If a participant engages in harassing behavior, MLH may take any action it deems appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the event with no eligibility for reimbursement or refund of any type.&lt
If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact MLH using the reporting procedures defined below.&lt

MLH representatives will be happy to help participants contact campus security or local law enforcement, provide escorts, or otherwise assist those experiencing harassment to feel safe for the duration of the event. We value your attendance.&lt
We expect participants to follow these rules at all hackathon venues, online interactions in relation to the event, hackathon-related social events, and on hackathon supplied transportation.&lt

If you feel uncomfortable or think there may be a potential violation of the code of conduct, please report it immediately using one of the following methods. All reporters have the right to remain anonymous.&lt
By sending information to the general reporting line, your report will go to any or all of the MLH representatives listed below.&lt
If you are uncomfortable reporting your situation to one or more of these people or need to contact any of them directly in case of emergency, direct contact details are listed below.&lt

MLH reserves the right to revise, make exceptions to, or otherwise amend these policies in whole or in part. If you have any questions regarding these policies, please contact MLH by e-mail at​ hi@mlh.io​.&lt
The competition is just a part of the hackathon. To make the most out of the event, try something new, teach other people, and make new friends!&lt

column5: Happy Hacking from the MLH team!&lt

column3: Develop a tech-based solution that targets a challenge or enhances learning experiences within the field of education. You have the freedom to choose the nature of your project – it can be a web application, mobile app, game, software tool, or any other innovative digital solution.&lt

column4: s functionality and features. Use this video to explain how your solution addresses the chosen educational challenge or enhances learning experiences. Be creative and engaging in your presentation.&lt

column3: Rules for TechHacks by TechTalks Hackathon (DATES TBD):&lt
TechHacks by TechTalks is open to participants of all ages, backgrounds, and skill levels, but it is primarily designed for beginner to intermediate coders.&lt
Participants under the age of 18 must have parental or guardian consent to participate.&lt
Teams can consist of 1 to 4 members. Each team member should meet the eligibility criteria.&lt
All submissions must be the original work of the participating teams. Plagiarism or the use of pre-existing solutions without proper attribution will result in disqualification.&lt
Projects should align with the hackathon theme of education and should aim to address challenges or enhance learning experiences in some way.&lt
While not mandatory, participants are encouraged to open-source their projects to promote knowledge sharing and collaboration within the coding community.&lt
Submissions must be completed and submitted by X (midnight), which is the official end time of the hackathon. Late submissions will not be accepted.&lt
Projects will be evaluated based on creativity, technical complexity, potential impact on education, and presentation quality.&lt

Participants retain intellectual property rights for their projects. However, by participating in TechHacks by TechTalks, you grant the organizers the right to use your project for promotional and educational purposes.&lt
The organizers reserve the right to disqualify any project or participant that violates the rules or engages in unethical behavior.&lt
Participants must comply with all applicable laws and regulations during the hackathon.&lt
The organizers reserve the right to make changes to the rules and guidelines as needed, with any updates communicated to participants.&lt
Our Discord Server features a wide variety of mentors and tutors for you to work with if you have any questions during the hackathon.&lt

column7: Context: Predicting product-related question responses using similar products&lt

column5: Predicting the response to a product-related question is an emerging research area that has recently gained a lot of attention. Responding to subjective, opinion-based questions is the most challenging due to the dependence on user-generated content. Previous work has mostly focused on response prediction based on reviews
column6: however, these approaches fail for new or unpopular products that have little (or no) reviews available.&lt

column5: A new method allows for accurately predicting the response to a product question, by leveraging knowledge from similar products.&lt

The goal is to automatically answer customer questions about products, a popular feature on e-commerce websites. However, when there are no relevant questions and answers in the archives, automatic tools struggle to provide adequate responses.&lt

Product Question Answering (PQA) aims to automatically answer customer questions to improve their online shopping experience. Current research mainly focuses on searching for answers in unstructured text, such as product descriptions and user reviews, or in structured knowledge bases with predefined schemas. Besides these two sources, much product information is represented in a semi-structured way, for example, in the form of key-value pairs, lists, tables, JSON and XML files, etc. This semi-structured data can be a valuable source of answers as it is better organized than free text, while being easier to construct than structured knowledge bases. However, little attention has been paid to it.&lt

column15: present semiPQA, a dataset for evaluating PQA on semi-structured data. It contains 11,243 human-written questions on JSON-formatted data covering 320 unique attribute types. column3: The Travel Prize will be awarded to an individual winner, or up to two people in a Team or Organisation (Travel Prize Recipient) and includes:
An invitation to attend Canva Extend on 25 September 2024 in San Francisco at Terra SF
Return economy class flights from an airport in the winners’ home city to an airport in San Francisco (unless the winner resides in California, in which case section 9 (E) below applies)

Two nights’ accommodation for each Travel Prize Recipient at accommodation of Sponsor’s choice (excluding extra costs incurred by the Travel Prize Recipients during their stay, such as room service). In the event that the Travel Prize Recipient is a Team or Organisation, Sponsor will provide one, twin-share room.  &lt
The Travel Prize Recipients’ home address and their home city airport
the destination airport and hotel accommodation

The value of the Travel Prize shall not exceed US$2,000 per traveler, and Sponsor shall not be required to expend more than that amount (“Value Limit”). If the actual value of the Travel Prize (as redeemed) is lower than the Value Limit, the difference in value shall be forfeit. Sponsor will not be required to provide additional components to the prize or cash substitutes to cover the discrepancy between the redeemed value and Value Limit. &lt

Travel Prize Recipients must be able to travel at the time of the Canva Extend conference. If any Travel Prize Recipients, or other members of a Team or Organisation, are unable to travel at that time, the Travel Prize will be forfeit and no substitute will be provided. &lt

The Travel Prize Recipients will liaise with Sponsor to organize the travel itinerary, which will be determined by Sponsor at its absolute discretion except as otherwise set out in these Terms and Conditions. Sponsor will be responsible for arranging the booking of flights, accommodation and transfers. Travel dates and flights are subject to availability, which will be confirmed at the point of booking. Sponsor reserves the right to propose alternative dates or accommodation.  &lt
If a Travel Prize Recipient resides in California, Sponsor will determine whether flight, train or other travel is more appropriate, and book or reimburse travel accordingly.&lt

If, for whatever reason, the Travel Prize Recipient cannot or does not want to accept the Travel Prize or does not go ahead with the Travel Prize after bookings have been made, then they forfeit the Travel Prize and Sponsor is not obliged to offer a substitute prize. &lt

Travel Prize includes sales or hotel tax directly applicable to the stated Travel Prize, however, any additional charges incurred during the stay must be settled with the hotel directly before departure. &lt
Travel Prize excludes spending money, meals, drinks, gratuities, excursions and incidental expenses incurred whilst on holiday other than those stated as included.&lt

Travel Prize Recipients must hold a valid passport from a country that is not forbidden or restricted by local laws and regulations at time of travel and that is valid for 6 months after the date of departure.&lt

Travel Prize Recipient is responsible for ensuring compliance with any necessary visa and other legal travel requirements and regulations prior to departure, travel vaccinations, subsistence, local currency, any local taxes and/or charges. &lt

Travel Prize Recipient is responsible for arranging their own travel insurance and health requirements, as well as checking any government or health authority travel advice for up-to-date requirements and restrictions relevant for travel to/from the destination and their country of residence.&lt

If flights are delayed or canceled, or the Travel Prize Recipient misses their flights or needs to change travel dates after booking for any reason whatsoever, the Travel Prize Recipient must seek advice directly from the relevant airline in accordance with the airline’s terms and conditions or from their travel insurance provider (as applicable).&lt

Sponsor is in no way responsible if the Travel Prize Recipient  is denied access to the destination country for any reason, and in such circumstances is not required to reschedule the Travel Prize, nor to provide an alternative prize or cash substitute.&lt
No component of the Travel Prize is transferable or redeemable for cash.&lt

column9: , our first hackathon experience hosted by the Seneca Software Developers Club! This challenge is to design and develop an innovative and visually stunning website for our club. Your mission is to create a platform that fosters a sense of community and collaboration among Seneca&#39

column4: ll have the freedom to work at your own pace, leveraging your creativity and technical skills to bring your ideas to life.&amp

column3: To embark on this exciting challenge, follow these detailed steps:&lt
Collaborate with 2 to 5 current Seneca students who bring diverse skills to the table. Ensure you have a good mix of designers and developers to cover all aspects of the project.&lt

column9: . Make sure to include all team members and contact information. Remember, you can edit your registration anytime before the deadline (June 28th, 11:59 PM) to make any necessary changes to your team composition.&lt

column3: Begin your project on June 24th at 9:00 AM. Work asynchronously, using version control systems (Git and Github recommended) to manage your code and keep track of changes.&lt
Create a website for the Seneca Software Developers Club that reflects creativity, functionality, and user engagement. Here are some key points to keep in mind when you build your hack:&lt

column5: While the main emphasis is on the frontend, if your backend significantly enhances the user experience, showcase it as well.&lt

column5: You have the freedom to create as many pages as needed. Whether it’s a single page or ten, ensure it represents the club’s essence and is scalable.&lt
Use the club’s design palette and pay attention to details. Refer to the rubric for judging criteria.&lt

column3: Ensure your final project is ready by June 30th, 11:59 PM. Check &lt

Good luck, and we can’t wait to see what you build!&lt

Creativity: Novelty and originality of the idea.&lt
Problem Solving: Uniqueness of the approach in addressing real world challenges.&lt
Relevance: Alignment with the chosen theme and addressing a significant issue.&lt
Potential Impact: Potential to positively impact outcomes, processes, or industry practices.&lt
Scalability: Consideration of scalability and sustainability of the solution in real-world settings.&lt
Clarity: Clear and concise communication of the problem statement, solution, and its features.&lt
Demonstration: Effectiveness of the video demo in showcasing the functionality and usability of the solution.&lt
Pitch Deck: Quality of the pitch deck slides in conveying key information and engaging the audience.&lt
Practicality: Feasibility of implementing the solution in real-world environments.&lt
Resource Requirements: Consideration of resource requirements (e.g., data, infrastructure) for deploying and maintaining the solution.&lt
Adaptability: Flexibility and adaptability of the solution to different contexts or settings.&lt
Ethical Considerations: Adherence to ethical principles and regulations in healthcare data usage, privacy, and security.&lt
Community Benefit: Potential to contribute to broader societal goals, such as reducing disparities or promoting public health.&lt

Please evaluate each project based on the above criteria and provide constructive feedback to help participants improve their solutions. Consider the context of the hackathon, the complexity of the challenges addressed, and the resources available to participants. The event is open to all who are interested in medical imaging and health IT. There are no costs to participate. column5: HackinMiami is a premier two-day event on June 15-16, 2024, featuring an AI-focused hackathon designed to showcase and elevate the vibrant tech ecosystem in Miami. This dynamic gathering connects developers, product managers, UI/UX designers, and AI enthusiasts to tackle pressing challenges in the local tech landscape through innovative solutions. Featuring dual tracks (General and HealthTech-focused), access to top AI tools, educational programming, and networking opportunities, HackinMiami fosters collaboration and empowers participants to create impactful technological advancements.&lt

column1: -Originality: How unique and creative is the solution? Does it offer a new approach to solving the problem?
-Innovative Use of Technology: How well does the solution leverage AI and other technologies? Are the technologies used in novel ways?
-Functionality: Does the solution work as intended? Is it free from significant bugs and issues?
-Potential Impact: What is the potential impact of the solution on the target users or market? Can it solve real-world problems effectively?
-Scalability: Can the solution be scaled to accommodate a larger audience or expanded functionality?
-User Interface: How intuitive and user-friendly is the interface? Is it visually appealing and easy to navigate?
-User Experience: How well does the solution meet the needs of the end-users? Is it accessible and inclusive?
-Clarity of Explanation: How well did the team explain their solution? Was the problem, solution, and technical implementation clearly articulated?
-Engagement: How engaging and compelling was the presentation?

column8: Whether you’re a Republican or Democrat, a Trump supporter, Biden supporter, or part of the exhausted majority - Americans’ confidence in our democratic institutions continues to wane, and for good reason. Unregulated campaign spending, voter suppression and partisan gerrymandering are corrupting our free and fair elections. Congress is too polarized to effectively legislate. Our information ecosystem is flooded with mis-and-disinformation, while algorithms inoculate us from diverse perspectives. Meanwhile, big tech continues to ‘move fast and break things’ at a pace that regulators can’t keep up with and at a scale that is damaging democracies around the world.&lt

This systemic dysfunction has sowed seeds of fear, uncertainty, distrust, and division that some experts argue put us at risk of increased political violence. It’s threatening our democracy as we know it, while also tearing our families and communities apart. All told, this leaves many feeling defeated, disillusioned and disempowered – rightly so.&amp

During this election season, when the feelings of anxiety and powerlessness are at a fever pitch, we are seeking solutions that give the public an opportunity to play a more active and empowered role in protecting our elections. In doing so, we hope to unite our users around a common goal – one that transcends the differences that divide us.&amp

column15: To narrow the sandbox, we will ask hackathon participants to explore solutions that accomplish these larger objectives specifically by leveraging gamification.&lt
column22: Gamification is the application of game-design elements and principles (such as badges, leaderboards, points, levels, and role-playing) in non-game contexts for the purpose of enhancing engagement and motivating behavior. Gamification has the power to rally diverse people around a common objective, to inspire action, and to inject fun and hope in unexpected places. For these reasons, we believe it is a particularly potent strategy for engaging, uniting, and re-inspiring an otherwise divided and disillusioned American public in the fight for our democracy.&amp
